  "body": "<!-- This form is for bug reports and feature requests ONLY!\r\n\r\nIf you're looking for help check [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/kubernetes) and the [troubleshooting guide](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug-application-cluster/troubleshooting/).\r\n\r\nIf this may be security issue, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Is this a BUG REPORT or FEATURE REQUEST?**:\r\n\r\n> Uncomment only one, leave it on its own line:\r\n>\r\n/kind bug\r\n> /kind feature\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nNodeAuthorizer prevents unmounting of CSI volumes when `terminationGracePeriod` is 0\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nVolume is unmounted without issue.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n1. Create a pod referencing a CSI volume and set `terminationGracePeriod` to 0.\r\n2. Delete the pod. This triggers the kubelet unmount logic on the CSI volume.\r\n3. Kubelet can not unmount the volume failing again and again with `node is not allowed access to resource persistentvolumes / pv-name`.\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\nThe node authorizer deletes prevents kubelet from fetching PV objects unless there is a pod referencing the PV object. When a pod is deleted with `terminationGracePeriod` is 0, the pod API object is deleted before the volume is unmounted. So when the CSI volume unmount code tries to fetch the PV object (https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/pkg/volume/csi/csi_attacher.go#L555) it fails because the node no longer has permission to access that object.\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Others:\r\n",
